# System Design Interview: URL Shortener

## Requirements

### Functional

1. Given a long URL, generate a short URL
2. Given a short URL, redirect to the original URL
3. URLs expire after a configurable TTL

### Non-Functional

- 100 million URLs generated per day
- 10:1 read-to-write ratio
- 99.99% availability
- Redirect latency under 100ms

## Capacity Estimation

Writes per second: $100M / 86400 \approx 1157$ writes/sec

Reads per second: $1157 \times 10 \approx 11570$ reads/sec

Storage for 5 years: $100M \times 365 \times 5 \times 500B \approx 91.25 TB$

## Key Generation

Use **base62 encoding** of a 7-character string:

$$
62^7 = 3.5 \times 10^{12}
$$

This gives us 3.5 trillion unique URLs, sufficient for our scale.

## Database Schema

| Field | Type | Description |
| --- | --- | --- |
| short_url | VARCHAR(7) | Primary key, base62 encoded |
| long_url | TEXT | Original URL |
| created_at | TIMESTAMP | Creation time |
| expires_at | TIMESTAMP | Expiration time |
| user_id | UUID | Creator (nullable) |

## Architecture

::: system-diagram
```
Client -> Load Balancer -> API Servers -> Cache (Redis)
                                      -> Database (Cassandra)
```
:::

### Components

API Server
: Handles URL creation and redirect requests
: Stateless, horizontally scalable

Cache Layer
: Redis cluster for hot URLs
: LRU eviction policy

Database
: Cassandra for distributed writes
: Tunable consistency levels

## Trade-offs

| Approach | Pros | Cons |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Pre-generated keys | No collision, fast | Key management complexity |
| Hash + collision check | Simple | Potential collisions |
| Counter-based | Sequential, unique | Single point of failure |

N> The pre-generated key approach is preferred at scale because it eliminates collision handling entirely.

